I talked to Steve Rajeff about casting after watching him cast during the Great Outdoor Games fly fishing tournament in 2001.  He had the best casting style for accuracy in the wind.  He would make a standard backcast a little high, then come forward with something like a stab cast, driving the fly into the target, very tournament style.(similar to double hauling with 20' of line like it is 40', just angled at the target)  If anyone tried to do it while fishing, they would scare the water out of the river.  I thought he was going to DESTROY the targerts I had taken so much time to build.  I do it when &quot;tournament casting,&quot; and it works great and very, very accurate.<br>
~Andrew <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flyfishar>FlyFishAR</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#000000>(2/24/03 4:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://boards.justflies.com/Images/4/4551Photo1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: certified casting instruction question</span><hr size=1> By the way Andrew I just got an email from Steve which I have forwarded on to you. If you want we can reply back and forth on here so that we can discuss the event in public?<br>
